1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,217
If you've ever played peekaboo and felt like your baby somehow knew

2
00:00:05,217 --> 00:00:09,565
what was coming, that intuition is backed by real developmental

3
00:00:09,565 --> 00:00:10,000
psychology.

4
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:13,000
Long before babies can talk, they're already predicting social

5
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:16,333
patterns, detecting cause and effect, and storing simple memories of

6
00:00:16,333 --> 00:00:17,000
new actions.

7
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:26,103
In this video, I'll walk through four classic infant experiments you

8
00:00:26,103 --> 00:00:36,862
can adapt at home, and how to do them without turning a playful

9
00:00:36,862 --> 00:00:41,000
observation into an overblown conclusion.

10
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:44,000
First, the big caveat: these are not diagnostic tests.

11
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:49,000
A single home session cannot tell you whether your baby is advanced,

12
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:53,583
delayed, or anything in between. Think of these as carefully observed

13
00:00:53,583 --> 00:00:54,000
games.

14
00:00:54,000 --> 00:01:09,407
For all four, use the same ground rules: choose a calm, alert baby,

15
00:01:09,407 --> 00:01:24,815
keep the room quiet, stop if your baby fusses, and keep the session

16
00:01:24,815 --> 00:01:26,000
short.

17
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:31,000
Experiment one is peekaboo, but done as a real protocol.

18
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:42,917
In the 1970s, Bruner argued that peekaboo works because it has a rigid

19
00:01:42,917 --> 00:01:50,250
structure: disappearance, suspense, and reveal. That gives babies

20
00:01:50,250 --> 00:01:53,000
something to predict.

21
00:01:53,000 --> 00:02:03,435
At home, keep the script identical for three or four trials: eye

22
00:02:03,435 --> 00:02:13,000
contact, the same ready cue, cover, pause two seconds, then reveal.

23
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:19,875
Once that baseline is stable, change one thing. Delay the reveal.

24
00:02:19,875 --> 00:02:23,000
Reveal from the wrong side.

25
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:27,783
What you're watching for is anticipation: a smile before the reveal,

26
00:02:27,783 --> 00:02:33,000
body tension during the pause, or eyes going where they expected you.

27
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:40,222
The point is not that your baby understands the game. It's that even

28
00:02:40,222 --> 00:02:46,889
this simple social routine is giving them a structure they can learn

29
00:02:46,889 --> 00:02:48,000
and predict.

30
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:52,125
Experiment two is the still-face paradigm, and this one is optional

31
00:02:52,125 --> 00:02:54,000
because it's the most sensitive.

32
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:57,333
Tronick's classic finding was that when a normally responsive parent

33
00:02:57,333 --> 00:03:00,000
suddenly goes neutral and unresponsive, babies protest quickly.

34
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:11,762
The home version is simple: one minute of normal warm play, up to

35
00:03:11,762 --> 00:03:19,000
thirty seconds of still face, then immediate reunion.

36
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:25,316
If your baby cries, turns red, or if you feel uncomfortable, stop

37
00:03:25,316 --> 00:03:29,000
right away. The reunion is not optional.

38
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:37,182
It shows that by four to five months, babies already expect social

39
00:03:37,182 --> 00:03:43,318
partners to respond contingently. When that pattern breaks, they

40
00:03:43,318 --> 00:03:44,000
notice.

41
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:46,000
Experiment three may be the most visually rewarding.

42
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:53,308
In the classic studies, babies learned that kicking made something

43
00:03:53,308 --> 00:04:02,808
happen overhead. At home, the safest version uses a floor play gym and

44
00:04:02,808 --> 00:04:05,000
full hands-on supervision.

45
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:09,125
First, watch two minutes of normal kicking with no connection. Then

46
00:04:09,125 --> 00:04:14,000
add a loose connection so kicking moves the toy. Then remove it again.

47
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:25,250
The observation lives in the contrast between phases. Does kicking

48
00:04:25,250 --> 00:04:39,875
become more deliberate when the toy responds? Do you see a burst after

49
00:04:39,875 --> 00:04:41,000
disconnect?

50
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:46,000
That's contingency detection: noticing that when I do this, that

51
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:52,000
happens. It's remarkable on its own. You don't need to inflate it.

52
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:57,000
Experiment four is imitation, and here the careful version matters.

53
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:01,136
The flashy claim that newborns imitate faces has not held up well. The

54
00:05:01,136 --> 00:05:04,000
stronger evidence comes a little later, with object actions.

55
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:09,280
Start with the easiest version: perform an unusual action with a

56
00:05:09,280 --> 00:05:15,040
rattle three times, then hand it over and wait silently. A partial

57
00:05:15,040 --> 00:05:16,000
copy counts.

58
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:28,960
For older babies, add a short delay: demonstrate, put the object away,

59
00:05:28,960 --> 00:05:41,920
do something else for ten minutes, then bring it back with no

60
00:05:41,920 --> 00:05:43,000
reminder.

61
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:48,500
What matters is not perfect copying. It's whether your baby retained

62
00:05:48,500 --> 00:05:52,000
some representation of the action they saw.

63
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:56,000
The difference between a home experiment and random play is how you

64
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:57,000
write it down.

65
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:08,870
Record what you saw, not what you think it means. "Baby kicked more"

66
00:06:08,870 --> 00:06:17,087
is an observation. "Baby understood cause and effect" is

67
00:06:17,087 --> 00:06:18,000
interpretation.

68
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:28,909
Timing, temperament, and sheer luck are huge confounders. A single

69
00:06:28,909 --> 00:06:40,909
trial is interesting. A pattern across different days is much more

70
00:06:40,909 --> 00:06:42,000
informative.

71
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:46,800
What I love about these experiments is not that they prove something

72
00:06:46,800 --> 00:06:50,000
grand. It's that they make early cognition visible.

73
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:58,762
Peekaboo lets you watch prediction. Still-face reveals social

74
00:06:58,762 --> 00:07:08,619
expectation. Kick-to-move shows cause and effect. Imitation gives you

75
00:07:08,619 --> 00:07:13,000
a glimpse of memory.
